Content.Question:
airplane

1868 , Eng. Mechanic & Mirror of Sci. “We have yet to see the ‘aëroplane’ with buoyancy sufficient to sustain 150 lb., or with apparatus sufficiently light and portable to make headway on an ‘air plane’.”

1874 , Belgravia “Not all the rudders and flappers..can ever enable the aeronaut to navigate his machine horizontally—to one hand or the other of the air-plane on which he is sailing.”

1891 , Amer. Naturalist “Its weight is resolved into a normal and parallel component by the air plane of pressure beneath it.”
Content.Answer:
airplane - In form air plane. A horizontal plane in the air on which an aircraft, bird, etc., is regarded as flying. Obsolete.
First use: Eng. Mechanic & Mirror of Sci.
Part of speech: NN
1868 - 1891
This sense is obsolete

Content.Question:
airplane

1896 J. Challis, Invention “The combined use of the screw and aeroplane (why not call it air plane) principles.”

1907 , Washington Post “My idea of the airship of the future. Somewhat on the order of a box-kite, with projecting air-planes on either side.”

1911 , Times “The rudders, airplanes, &c. are worked from the gondolas, where compasses and other navigating appliances are also arranged.”
Content.Answer:
airplane - = aeroplane n. 1. Now rare.
First use: J. Challis
Part of speech: NN
1896 -

Content.Question:
airplane

1906 , Sci. Amer. “Air-plane is a much better word than aeroplane. It is as good etymologically, and much better when it is spoken.”

1907 , Westm. Gaz. “It is this ease of going against the current, with no motive force in evidence, that is..the despair of the aeronauts with their air-planes.”

1917 , N.A.C.A. (U.S.) Rep. Nomencl. Aeronaut. “Airplane..This term is commonly used in a more restricted sense to refer to airplanes fitted with landing gear suited to operation from the land. If the landing gear is suited to operation from the water, the term ‘Seaplane’ is used.”

1933 E. A. Powell, Slanting Lines of Steel “This was no airplane bomb, but a projectile from a super-cannon.”

1978 D. B. Thurston, Design for Flying “If the airplane is intended for the..private market, thin skin could be used and the weight saved converted to useful load.”

1995 , Mail on Sunday “No one with any sanity would fly in an airplane if they could walk.”

2005 , Chicago Sun-Times “New rules that would allow travelers to bring items such as sharp knives and scissors onto airplanes, rolling back post-9/11 prohibitions.”
Content.Answer:
airplane - Chiefly North American = aeroplane n. 2. Also attributive.
First use: Scientific American
Part of speech: NN
1906 -
This is the main current sense
